  "-0.09375 mpg per mph": "",
  "0.15625 mpg per mph": "",
  "First simplify: E(v) = (60v - 0.5v^2)/(v+10). E'(v) = [(60-v)(v+10) - (60v-0.5v^2)(1)]/(v+10)^2. At v=30: numerator = (30)(40) - (1800-450) = 1200 - 1350 = -150. Wait -- let me recalculate: (60-30)(40) - (1800-450) = 1200-1350 = -150. E'(30) = -150/1600. Let me recheck the problem. Actually E'(30) = [(60-v)(v+10) - (60v-0.5v^2)]/(v+10)^2 = [600+60*10-v^2-10v-60v+0.5v^2]/(v+10)^2. This needs careful expansion.": "",
  "A scientist models a chemical concentration as C(t) = t^2 * e^(-t) mg/L. Using the product rule, when does the concentration reach its peak (C'(t) = 0, t > 0)?": "",
  "t = 2 hours": "",
  "t = 0.5 hours": "",
  "t = 1 hour": "",
  "C'(t) = 2t*e^(-t) + t^2*(-e^(-t)) = e^(-t)(2t - t^2) = e^(-t)*t(2-t). Setting C'(t) = 0 for t > 0: t(2-t) = 0 gives t = 2 hours.": "",
  "A real estate agent models home prices as P(t) = (200 + 5t)(1000 + 50t) dollars, where t is years from now. What is the rate of increase in home prices at t = 0?": "",
